1. Cut Services to the Minimum Viable Set
Don't build all 7 services. Pick the ones that demonstrate the most architectural surface area:

Service	Why Include
claims-service
Core domain, state machine, event publisher
notification-service
Kafka consumer, fan-out pattern, Node.js (different tech = polyglot)
document-service
File handling, storage port pattern, async S3
api-gateway
Spring Cloud Gateway (lighter than Kong for POC)
auth
Keycloak (just run it, don't code it)
Leave workflow, payments, reporting, workshops as stubs — a Spring Boot app with one /health endpoint and a TODO.md explaining its role. That still demonstrates the decomposition without the build cost.

2. Use Spring Cloud Gateway Instead of Kong
For a small-scale POC, Kong has too much operational overhead (needs its own DB, config API, admin portal). Use Spring Cloud Gateway instead:

It's a Spring Boot app — same stack, easy to code route config.
Handles JWT validation via Keycloak, rate limiting, routing, CORS in YAML config.
Much faster to set up and demonstrates the same API gateway concept.
# application.yml in gateway service
spring:
  cloud:
    gateway:
      routes:
        - id: claims-service
          uri: http://claims-service:8081
          predicates:
            - Path=/api/v1/claims/**
        - id: document-service
          uri: http://document-service:8082
          predicates:
            - Path=/api/v1/documents/**
3. Each Service Gets Its Own Database Schema (Same Postgres Instance)
For small scale, running one Postgres with separate schemas per service is the right call. It simulates database isolation without running 5 DB containers:

postgres container
  └── eclaims DB
       ├── schema: claims         (owned by claims-service only)
       ├── schema: documents      (owned by document-service only)
       ├── schema: notifications  (owned by notification-service only)
       └── schema: audit          (append-only, written by all via event)
Each service gets its own DB user with GRANT only on its own schema. This makes the boundary tangible.

4. Service-to-Service Communication Strategy
Call Type	Use	Example
User-initiated (sync)
REST via gateway
Customer submits claim → claims-service
State propagation (async)
Kafka events
Claims-service publishes → notification-service consumes
Internal service lookup (sync)
OpenFeign with circuit breaker
Claims-service calls document-service for doc list
Avoid direct DB calls across services — this is the #1 thing that distinguishes a real microservice from a "distributed monolith".

5. Docker Compose — One File to Run Everything
Structure your docker-compose.yml so the evaluator can run docker compose up and see everything:

services:
  postgres          → port 5432
  redpanda          → port 9092  (Kafka)
  redpanda-console  → port 8082  (topic UI — visually impressive for demo)
  redis             → port 6379
  keycloak          → port 8080
  gateway-service   → port 8090  (Spring Cloud Gateway)
  claims-service    → port 8081  (internal only, behind gateway)
  document-service  → port 8082  (internal only)
  notification-svc  → port 8083  (Node.js NestJS)
  frontend          → port 5173  (React, Nginx in container)
This is the single strongest thing you can do for the evaluation — a working docker compose up --build that boots the entire system in under 2 minutes says more than 1000 lines of documentation.

6. Feature Scope per Service (Ruthless Minimum)
Service	Build Only This
claims-service
Submit claim, get claim by ID, update status (SUBMITTED → ASSIGNED → APPROVED), publish ClaimSubmittedEvent + ClaimStatusChangedEvent to Kafka
document-service
Upload document (local filesystem), get documents by claim ID
notification-service
Consume Kafka events, log to console + send one real email via Spring Mail (or Mailhog locally)
gateway-service
Route /claims/** and /documents/**, validate JWT, rate limit
frontend
Login page, submit claim form, view claim status timeline
That's it. Each service has ~5–8 REST endpoints and one Kafka topic interaction. But the architecture is real, the boundaries are real, and it deploys.

7. Add Mailhog for Email (Visible Notification Demo)
Instead of real AWS SES or Twilio, use Mailhog — a local SMTP catcher that has a browser UI at localhost:8025. When a claim is submitted, the evaluator can literally see the notification email arrive in the Mailhog inbox. Very high visual impact for demos.

mailhog:
  image: mailhog/mailhog
  ports:
    - "8025:8025"   # Web UI
    - "1025:1025"   # SMTP
Spring Mail config:

spring.mail.host: localhost
spring.mail.port: 1025
8. Key Things That Score High on Evaluation
docker compose up --build works — evaluator can run it themselves.
ArchUnit tests in each service proving dependency direction (domain never imports Spring).
Swagger UI (/swagger-ui.html) on each service — shows API contract thinking.
Kafka topic visible in Redpanda Console UI — shows event-driven architecture is live.
Keycloak admin shows 8 roles + test users — shows RBAC is real, not hardcoded.
Each service's README.md explains its bounded context, ports, and how it maps to the solution architecture doc.
Correlation ID in logs flowing across services — shows distributed tracing awareness.